nt.time.com/time/business/article/0,8599,1865467,00.html|publisher=Time Magazine|accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=townes>{{cite web|last1=Townes|first1=John|title=Interview: \"Small is Beautiful\"|url=http://jtgallery.net/resume/22/|publisher=Berkshire Trade and Commerce|accessdate=17 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=utne>{{cite web|last1=Stonington|first1=Joel|title=Local Currencies Aren't Small Change|url=http://www.utne.com/community/localcurrenciesarentsmallchange.aspx?PageId=1|publisher=[[Utne Reader]]|accessdate=25 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=yale>{{cite web|title=People, Land, and Community Collected E. F. Schumacher Society Lectures|url=http://yalepress.yale.edu/yupbooks/book.asp?isbn=0300071736|publisher=[[Yale University Press]]|accessdate=17 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=yesshare>{{cite web|last1=Golden|first1=Jeff|title=3 Ways to Invest in Your Community|url=http://www.yesmagazine.org/issues/the-new-economy/3-ways-to-invest-in-your-community|publisher=[[Yes!_(U.S._magazine)|Yes!]]|accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.centerforneweconomics.org/ Schumacher Center For a New Economics]\n* [http://communitylandtrust.org/ Community Land Trust in the Southern Berkshires]\n\n\n[[Category:Sustainability organizations]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Berkshire County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Economics libraries]]\n[[Category:Think tanks established in 1980]]\n[[Category:Political and economic think tanks in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schumacher_Center_for_a_New_Economics"}
{"title_page": "HubSpot", "text_new": "{{short description|American marketing software company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = HubSpot, Inc.\n| logo             = HubSpot Logo.svg\n| type             = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as        = {{NYSE|HUBS}}<br />[[Russell 2000 Index|Russell 2000 Component]]\n| founders         = [[Brian Halligan]] <br /> [[Dharmesh Shah]]\n| key_people       = Brian Halligan ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])<br />JD Sherman [[Chief operating officer|COO]]<br />Kate Bueker [[CFO]]<br />Kipp Bodnar [[Chief marketing officer|CMO]]<br />[[Dharmesh Shah]] ([[Chief technology officer|CTO]])\n| num_employees    = 3,387 (2020)<ref>{{Cite news |title= HubSport Company Profile |work= Craft |url= https://craft.co/hubspot | accessdate= March 4, 2020 }}</ref>\n| industry         = Software\n| revenue          = {{Unbulleted list|{{increase}}[[United States dollar|US]]$674.9 million (2019)<ref name=\"hubspot_2019\">{{cite web|title=HubSpot Reports Full Year 2019 Results|url=https://craft.co/hubspot|website=Craft |publisher=Craft, Inc.|accessdate = 13 March 2019}}</ref>}}\n| operating_income = {{Unbulleted list|{{increase}}US$-40.1 million (2017)<ref name=\"hubspot_2017\">{{cite web|title=HubSpot Reports Strong Q4 and Full Year 2017 Results|url=https://s2.q4cdn.com/235752014/files/doc_news/HubSpot-Reports-Strong-Q4-and-Full-Year-2017-Results.pdf|website=HubSpot |publisher=HubSpot, Inc.|accessdate = August 1, 2018 |format=PDF}}</ref>}}\n| net_income       = {{Unbulleted list|{{decrease}}[[United States dollar|US]]$-63.83 million (2018)<ref name=\"hubspot_2018\">{{cite web|title=HubSpot Reports Full Year 2018 Results|url=https://craft.co/hubspot|website=Craft |publisher=Craft, Inc.|accessdate = 13 March 2019}}</ref>}}\n| net_income_year  = <!-- or: | profit_year = --><!-- Year of net_income/profit data (if known) -->\n| assets           = {{Unbulleted list|{{increase}}US$712 million (2017)<ref name=\"hubspot_2017\" /> }}\n| assets_year      = <!-- Year of assets data (if known) -->\n| equity           = {{Unbulleted list|{{increase}}US$210.3 million (2017)<ref name=\"hubspot_2017\" />}}\n| equity_year      = <!-- Year of equity data (if known) -->\n| homepage         = {{URL|http://www.hubspot.com/}}\n| location_city    = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]\n| foundation       = June 2006\n}}\n\n'''HubSpot''' is an American developer and marketer of [[software]] products for [[inbound marketing]], sales, and customer service. It was founded by [[Brian Halligan]] and Dharmesh Shah in 2006.\n\nIts products and services aim to provide tools for [[customer relationship management]], [[social media marketing]], [[content management]], [[lead generation]], [[web analytics]], [[search engine optimization]], live chat, and customer support.\n\n==History==\n[[File:HubSpot Offices2.png|thumb|250px|right|Interior view of HubSpot's office space]]\nHubSpot was founded by [[Brian Halligan]] and Dharmesh Shah at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT) in 2006.<ref name=\"onehundredsixtyseven\">{{cite news| last =Stone| first =Avery| title =HubSpot wants to be Salesforce.com for small business| newspaper =Fortune Magazine| date =August 8, 2011| url =http://tech.fortune.cnn.com/2011/08/08/hubspot-wants-to-be-salesforce-com-for-small-business/| accessdate =February 27, 2012| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20120303123644/http://tech.fortune.cnn.com/2011/08/08/hubspot-wants-to-be-salesforce-com-for-small-business/| archive-date =March 3, 2012| url-status =dead}}</ref>\n\nThe company grew from $255,000 in revenues in 2007 to $15.6 million in 2010.<ref name=\"onehundredsixtyseven\"/><ref>{{cite news| last =Alspach| first =Kyle| title =HubSpot: We plan to be like HP, a huge company that lasts 100 years. But in Cambridge| newspaper =Boston Business Journal| date =December 15, 2011| url =http://www.bizjournals.com/boston/blog/startups/2011/12/hubspot-we-plan-to-be-like-hp-a-big.html| accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref>  Later that year HubSpot acquired Oneforty, the [[Twitter]] app store founded by [[Laura Fitton]].<ref name=\"onehundredseventytwo\">{{cite news| last =Rao| first =Leena| title =HubSpot Buys Social Media Management Platform And App Directory Oneforty| newspaper =TechCrunch| date =August 18, 2011| url =https://techcrunch.com/2011/08/18/hubspot-buys-social-media-management-platform-and-app-directory-oneforty/| accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"onehundredseventythree\">{{cite news| last =O\u2019Dell| first =Jolie| title =Twitter app store Oneforty acquired by HubSpot| newspaper =VentureBeat| date =August 18, 2011| url =https://venturebeat.com/2011/08/18/oneforty-acquisition/| accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref> The company also introduced new software for personalizing websites to each visitor.<ref>{{cite news| last =Alspach| first =Kyle| title =HubSpot: What we're working on now will change the Internet| newspaper =Boston Business Journal| date =December 14, 2011| url =http://www.bizjournals.com/boston/blog/startups/2011/12/hubspot-amazon-personalization-marketing.html| accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref> According to ''Forbes'', HubSpot started out targeting small companies but \"moved steadily upmarket to serve larger businesses of up to 1000 employees.\"<ref name=\"\u201ccrm\">{{cite news|first=Chuck|last=Schaeffer|url=http://www.crmsearch.com/hubspot-review.php|publisher=CRMSearch|title=HubSpot Marketing Software Review\u2014An Independent Marketing Software Analysis|accessdate=January 27, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite news|title=HubSpot Looks to Pounce as Traditional Marketing Gets \"Obliterated\"|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jjcolao/2012/03/15/hubspot-ready-to-pounce-as-traditional-marketing-gets-obliterated/|first=J.J.|last=Colao|date=March 15, 2012|accessdate=December 29, 2013|work=Forbes}}</ref> HubSpot filed for an initial public offering with the Securities and Exchange Commission on August 25, 2014, requesting they be listed on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] under the ticker symbol HUBS.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1404655/000119312514320044/d697256ds1.htm|title=S-1|publisher=}}</ref> In July 2017, HubSpot acquired Kemvi, which applies artificial intelligence and machine learning to help sales teams.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/07/25/hubspot-acquires-kemvi/|title=HubSpot acquires Kemvi to bring more AI into its sales and marketing platform|last=Ha|first=Anthony|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2017-11-02|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Software and services==\nHubSpot provides  tools for [[social media marketing]], [[content management]], [[web analytics]], [[landing pages]], [[customer support]], and [[search engine optimization]].<ref name=\"onehundredsixtyseven\"/><ref name=\"wsjj\">{{cite news|title=\nGoogle Ventures, Sequoia, Salesforce Give HubSpot $32M|date=March 8, 2011|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2011/03/08/google-ventures-sequoia-salesforce-give-hubspot-32m/|accessdate=December 27, 2013|first=Deborah|last=Gage}}</ref><ref name=\"harvard\"/><ref name=\"onehundredfiftythree\">{{cite news\n | last =McCarthy\n | first =Kevin\n | title =The Tech Behind HubSpot\n | newspaper =BostInno\n | date =May 26, 2011\n | url =http://bostinno.com/2011/05/26/the-tech-behind-hubspot/\n | accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2018/05/11/hubspot-service-hub/|title=HubSpot adds customer service tools to its marketing platform|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref>\nHubSpot has integration features for [[salesforce.com]], [[SugarCRM]], [[NetSuite]], [[Microsoft Dynamics CRM]] and others.<ref>{{cite news\n | last =Greenberg\n | first =Paul\n | title =CRM Watchlist 2012 Winners \u2013 The Marketing Mavens\n | newspaper =ZDNet\n | date =January 24, 2012\n | url =http://www.zdnet.com/blog/crm/crm-watchlist-2012-winners-the-marketing-mavens/4074\n | accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref>  There are also third-party services such as templates and extensions.<ref>{{citation|url=http://marketplace.hubspot.com/|title=Marketplace|publisher=HubSpot|accessdate=December 27, 2013}}</ref> Additionally, HubSpot offers consulting services and an online resource academy for learning inbound marketing tactics.<ref name=\"onehundredeighty\">{{cite news\n | last =Blackwell\n | first =Gerry\n | title =HubSpot: The Evolution of Marketing\n | publisher =Small Business Computing\n | date =January 16, 2008\n | url =http://www.smallbusinesscomputing.com/biztools/article.php/3722071/HubSpot-The-Evolution-of-Marketing.htm\n | accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"thirtysix\"/> It also hosts user group conferences and inbound marketing and certification programs.<ref name=\"thirtysix\">{{citation|url=http://academy.hubspot.com/|title=HubSpot Academy|accessdate=December 26, 2013|date=May 18, 2009}}</ref>  HubSpot promotes their [[inbound marketing]] concepts through their own marketing,<ref name=\"harvard\">{{citation|title=HubSpot: Inbound Marketing and Web 2.0|first1=Thomas|last1=Steenburgh|first2=Jilly |last2=Avery |first3= Naseem |last3= Dahod|date=January 24, 2011|url=http://hbr.org/product/hubspot-inbound-marketing-and-web-2-0/an/509049-PDF-ENG|accessdate=December 30, 2013}}</ref> and has been called \"a prolific creator of content\" such as blogs, social media, webinars and white papers.<ref name=\"\u201ccrm\"/>\n\nIn 2010, an article in the ''Harvard Business Review'' said that HubSpot's most effective inbound marketing feature was its free online tools.<ref name=\"afgty\">{{cite news|title=HubSpot\u2019s New Alerts Grader Cures Social Media Email Overload|url=http://bostinno.streetwise.co/2010/04/27/inundated-with-emails-try-hubspots-alert-grader/|publisher=BostInno|date=April 27, 2010|first=Kyle|last=Psaty|accessdate=December 28, 2013}}</ref> One such tool, the Marketing Grader, assessed and scored website performance.<ref name=\"onehundredeightytwo\">{{cite news| last =Ha| first =Anthony| title =Marketing software company HubSpot raises $12M| newspaper =VentureBeat| date =May 16, 2008| url =https://venturebeat.com/2008/05/16/marketing-software-company-hubspot-raises-12m/| accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"onehundredfive\">{{cite news\n | last =Gomer\n | first =Gregory\n | title =HubSpot Marketing Grader Launches: We Put 30 Boston Startups Head to Head #Deathmatch\n | newspaper =Bostinno\n | date =December 6, 2011\n | url =http://bostinno.com/2011/12/06/hubspot-marketing-grader-launches-we-put-30-boston-startups-head-to-head-deathmatch/\n | accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref> The company introduced a Twitter tracking feature in 2011.<ref name=\"onehundredsixtyeight\">{{cite news\n | last =Gomer\n | first =Gregory\n | title =HubSpot Powers Useful Tool to Track ReTweets, Suffers Unfortunate Name: WhoretweetedMe\n | publisher =BostonInno\n | date = August 10, 2011\n | url =http://bostinno.com/2011/08/10/hubspot-powers-useful-tool-to-track-retweets-suffers-unfortunate-name-whoretweetedme/\n | accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"onehundredseventyone\">{{cite news\n | last =Dugan\n | first =Lauren\n | title =Find Out Which Influencers Retweeted You\n | publisher =MediaBistro\n | date =August 16, 2011\n | url =http://www.mediabistro.com/alltwitter/find-out-which-influencers-retweeted-you_b12750\n | accessdate =February 27, 2012\n | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20120114134803/http://www.mediabistro.com/alltwitter/find-out-which-influencers-retweeted-you_b12750\n | archive-date =January 14, 2012\n | url-status =dead\n }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, HubSpot launched HubSpot Academy, an online training platform that provides various digital marketing training programs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hubspot.com/company-news/hubspot-academy-launches-new-content-marketing-certification-with-a-lesson-on-topic-clusters|title=HubSpot Academy Launches New Content Marketing Certification With a Lesson on Topic Clusters|last=Flanagan|first=Ellie|website=www.hubspot.com|access-date=2019-10-03}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Hubspot integrated [[Taboola]] on the dashboard, a global [[pay-per-click]] native ad network.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ppc.land/hubspot-is-now-connected-with-taboola/|title=HubSpot is now connected with Taboola|last=Rijo|first=Daniel|date=June 3, 2018|work=PPC Land|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Hubspot acquired PieSync, a customer data [[synchronization]] platform.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/hubspot-acquires-piesync-the-highest-reviewed-data-syncing-ipaas-to-enable-a-consistent-view-of-customers-across-hundreds-of-different-technologies-300950685.html | title=HubSpot Acquires PieSync | work=[[PR Newswire]] | date=November 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===HubSpot CRM Free===\nThe company launched '''HubSpot CRM Free''' in 2014.<ref name=\"Salager14\">{{cite news |title=The effect of HubSpot's CRM launch on Salesforce |last1=Salager |first1=Serge |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/12/10/is-hubspots-crm-launch-a-declaration-of-war-to-salesforce/ |newspaper=TechCrunch |date=10 December 2014 |accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> The CRM product tracks and manages interactions between a company and its customers and prospects. It enables companies to forecast revenue, measure sales team productivity, and report on revenue sources.<ref name=\"Brooks17\">{{cite web |url=https://www.businessnewsdaily.com/10071-best-crm-tools-startup.html |title=HubSpot review: Best CRM software for startups |author=Chad Brooks |date=12 July 2017 |publisher=Business News Daily |accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Maloney16\">{{cite news |title=14 free business tools to make your startup more successful in 2017 |last1=Maloney |first1=Kathleen |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/kathleen-maloney/14-free-business-tools-to_b_13718746.html |newspaper=[[HuffPost]] |date=19 December 2016 |accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"William17\">{{cite news |title=Best CRMs for SMBs in 2017 |last1=Williams |first1=Mike |url=http://www.techradar.com/news/software/business-software/10-crm-systems-small-businesses-should-know-1250344 |newspaper=[[TechRadar]] |date=13 July 2017 |accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> The [[software as a service]] product is free and integrates with [[Gmail]], [[G Suite]], [[Microsoft Office]] for [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], and other software.<ref name=\"Houpes15\">{{cite web |url=http://searchcrm.techtarget.com/feature/What-to-expect-from-the-HubSpot-CRM-platform |title=What to expect from the HubSpot CRM platform |author=T.J. Houpes |date=25 September 2015 |publisher=TechTarget |accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Tech industry reviews===\nHubSpot has been described as unique because it strives to provide its customers with an all-in-one approach.<ref name=\"onehundredfiftythree\"/><ref name=\"onehundredseventyeight\">{{cite news\n | last =Roush\n | first =Wade\n | title =Online Marketing for Dummies\u2014and for People with Better Things to Do\n | newspaper =Xconomy\n | date =August 24, 2007\n | URL =http://www.xconomy.com/boston/2007/08/24/online-marketing-for-dummies-and-for-people-with-better-things-to-do/\n | access date =February 27, 2012 }}</ref> A 2012 review in CRM Search said HubSpot was not the best business solution in each category but that taken as a whole it was the best \"marketing solution\" that combined many tools into one package.<ref name=\"\u201cCRM\"/> It identified HubSpot's \"strengths\" as the sophistication of its Call to Action (CTA) tool, its online ecosystem and its \"ease of use.\"  Its weakness was described as having \"more breadth than depth.\" The review said the lack of customization and design tools could be limiting and that it was missing advanced features such as [[Business Process Management]] (BPM) tools to manage workflow.<ref name=\"\u201cCRM\"/>\n\n===Conferences===\nHubSpot hosts an annual marketing conference for HubSpot users and partners called \"Inbound.\" The conference is typically located in Boston. In 2019, they had the largest of the conferences in the event history with a record of over 26,000 attendees.<ref name=\"onehundredeightyfive\">{{cite news\n | title =Takeaways from HubSpot INBOUND 2018\n | newspaper =CMS Newswire\n | date =February 7, 2019\n | URL =https://www.cmswire.com/digital-marketing/takeaways-from-hubspot-inbound-2018/\n | access date =February 7, 2019 }}</ref><ref>https://gritdaily.com/recap-inbound-2019/</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn July 2015, Hubspot's CMO, Mike Volpe, was dismissed for violating HubSpot's code of business conduct after it was found that he tried to obtain a draft copy of the book ''[[Disrupted: My Misadventure in the Start-Up Bubble]],'' written by his former employee [[Daniel Lyons]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.betaboston.com/news/2015/07/29/hubspot-fires-marketing-chief-sanctions-ceo-over-incident-involving-book-about-the-company/|title=HubSpot fires marketing chief, sanctions CEO over an incident involving book about the company|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://fortune.com/disrupted-excerpt-hubspot-startup-dan-lyons/ My Year in Startup Hell], Dan Lyons in ''Fortune'', April 2016</ref> According to an article in the ''[[Boston Globe]]'', records obtained under the [[Freedom of Information Act]] indicated that HubSpot executives considered the book \"a financial threat to HubSpot\" and Volpe used \"tactics such as email hacking and extortion\" in the attempt to prevent the book from being published.<ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2016/03/23/documents-released-hubspot-probe-involving-author-dan-lyons/VZH4CN4kR5p7iyhsKEdwJI/story.html Extortion, hacking claims sparked HubSpot investigation, FBI records show], Boston Globe, 24 March 2016</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, after his book was published, Lyons wrote in the ''[[New York Times]]'' that HubSpot had a \"frat house\" atmosphere. He also called the company a \"digital sweatshop\" in which workers had little job security.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/10/opinion/sunday/congratulations-youve-been-fired.html|title=Congratulations! You\u2019ve Been Fired|first=Dan|last=Lyons|date=9 April 2016|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Later that month, HubSpot's founders gave an official response to the book, in which they addressed several, but not all, of Lyons' claims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2016/04/12/hubspot-finally-responds-to-dan-lyons-book/|title=HubSpot (Finally) Responds to Dan Lyons' Book|publisher=Fortune|date=12 April 2016|author=Primack, Dan}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe ''[[Boston Business Journal]]'' named HubSpot a \"Best Place to Work in 2012.\"<ref name=\"onehundredfiftysix\">{{cite news\n | last =Regan\n | first =Keith\n | title =Hubspot's West Coast attitude gets talent\n | newspaper =Boston Business Journal\n | date =June 10, 2011\n | url =http://www.bizjournals.com/boston/print-edition/2011/06/10/hubspots-west-coast-attitude-gets.html\n | accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref> In 2015, the company was named the best large company to work for in Massachusetts by the ''Boston Globe''.<ref>Sarah Shemkus,[https://www.bostonglobe.com/magazine/2015/11/12/hubspot-tops-list-large-companies/sb6hujhzpWq7BFyYXbFvAP/story.html \"HubSpot Tops List of Large Companies,\"] Boston Globe, 12 November 2015 (page visited 16 June 2016)</ref><ref name=\"onehundredfiftytwo\">\n{{cite news\n | title =8 companies with the best vacation perks\n | newspaper =CNN Money\n | date =June 6, 2011\n | url =http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2011/pf/jobs/1105/gallery.best_vacation_policies.fortune/5.html\n | accessdate =February 27, 2012\n | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20120428064157/http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2011/pf/jobs/1105/gallery.best_vacation_policies.fortune/5.html\n | archive-date =April 28, 2012\n | url-status =dead\n | df =mdy-all\n }}\n</ref> In 2017, Hubspot was named 7th by CNBC as one of the best places to work in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/12/05/the-10-best-companies-to-work-for-in-2018.html|title=These are the best places to work in 2018|last=Dickler|first=Jessica|date=2017-12-06|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref> [[Glassdoor]] named Hubspot the best place to work in 2020.<ref>[https://www.glassdoor.com/Award/Best-Places-to-Work-LST_KQ0,19.htm Best Places to Work 2020] [[Glassdoor]]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book\n | last =Lyons\n | first =Daniel\n | title =Disrupted: My Misadventure in the Start Up Bubble\n | publisher =Hachette Books\n | year =2016\n | isbn =978-0316306089 }}\n* {{cite book\n | last =Halligan\n | first =Brian |author2=David Meerman Scott |author3=Dharmesh Shah\n | title =Inbound Marketing: Get Found Using Google, Social Media and Blogs\n | publisher =John Wiley & Sons, Inc.\n | year =2010\n | isbn =978-0-470-49931-3 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|HubSpot}}\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.hubspot.com}}\n*[https://blog.hubspot.com Hubspot Blog]\n*[https://academy.hubspot.com Hubspot Academy]\n\n{{Portal bar|Business|Companies|Economics|Internet|United States|Society}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hubspot}}\n[[Category:Technology companies based in the Boston area]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Cambridge, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Marketing companies established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Digital marketing companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Search engine optimization]]\n[[Category:Software companies based in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Web analytics]]\n[[Category:Marketing software]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:CRM software companies]]\n[[Category:Software companies of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American marketing software company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = HubSpot, Inc.\n| logo             = HubSpot Logo.svg\n| type             = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as        = {{NYSE|HUBS}}<br />[[Russell 2000 Index|Russell 2000 Component]]\n| founders         = [[Brian Halligan]] <br /> [[Dharmesh Shah]]\n| key_people       = Brian Halligan ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])<br />JD Sherman [[Chief operating officer|COO]]<br />Kate Bueker [[CFO]]<br />Kipp Bodnar [[Chief marketing officer|CMO]]<br />[[Dharmesh Shah]] ([[Chief technology officer|CTO]])\n| num_employees    = 3,387 (2020)<ref>{{Cite news |title= HubSport Company Profile |work= Craft |url= https://craft.co/hubspot | accessdate= March 4, 2020 }}</ref>\n| industry         = Software\n| revenue          = {{Unbulleted list|{{increase}}[[United States dollar|US]]$674.9 million (2019)<ref name=\"hubspot_2019\">{{cite web|title=HubSpot Reports Full Year 2019 Results|url=https://craft.co/hubspot|website=Craft |publisher=Craft, Inc.|accessdate = 13 March 2019}}</ref>}}\n| operating_income = {{Unbulleted list|{{increase}}US$-40.1 million (2017)<ref name=\"hubspot_2017\">{{cite web|title=HubSpot Reports Strong Q4 and Full Year 2017 Results|url=https://s2.q4cdn.com/235752014/files/doc_news/HubSpot-Reports-Strong-Q4-and-Full-Year-2017-Results.pdf|website=HubSpot |publisher=HubSpot, Inc.|accessdate = August 1, 2018 |format=PDF}}</ref>}}\n| net_income       = {{Unbulleted list|{{decrease}}[[United States dollar|US]]$-63.83 million (2018)<ref name=\"hubspot_2018\">{{cite web|title=HubSpot Reports Full Year 2018 Results|url=https://craft.co/hubspot|website=Craft |publisher=Craft, Inc.|accessdate = 13 March 2019}}</ref>}}\n| net_income_year  = <!-- or: | profit_year = --><!-- Year of net_income/profit data (if known) -->\n| assets           = {{Unbulleted list|{{increase}}US$712 million (2017)<ref name=\"hubspot_2017\" /> }}\n| assets_year      = <!-- Year of assets data (if known) -->\n| equity           = {{Unbulleted list|{{increase}}US$210.3 million (2017)<ref name=\"hubspot_2017\" />}}\n| equity_year      = <!-- Year of equity data (if known) -->\n| homepage         = {{URL|http://www.hubspot.com/}}\n| location_city    = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]\n| foundation       = June 2006\n}}\n\n'''HubSpot''' is an American developer and marketer of [[software]] products for [[inbound marketing]], sales, and customer service. It was founded by [[Brian Halligan]] and Dharmesh Shah in 2006.\n\nIts products and services aim to provide tools for [[customer relationship management]], [[social media marketing]], [[content management]], [[lead generation]], [[web analytics]], [[search engine optimization]], live chat, and customer support.\n\n==History==\n[[File:HubSpot Offices2.png|thumb|250px|right|Interior view of HubSpot's office space]]\nHubSpot was founded by [[Brian Halligan]] and Dharmesh Shah at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT) in 2006.<ref name=\"onehundredsixtyseven\">{{cite news| last =Stone| first =Avery| title =HubSpot wants to be Salesforce.com for small business| newspaper =Fortune Magazine| date =August 8, 2011| url =http://tech.fortune.cnn.com/2011/08/08/hubspot-wants-to-be-salesforce-com-for-small-business/| accessdate =February 27, 2012| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20120303123644/http://tech.fortune.cnn.com/2011/08/08/hubspot-wants-to-be-salesforce-com-for-small-business/| archive-date =March 3, 2012| url-status =dead}}</ref>\n\nThe company grew from $255,000 in revenues in 2007 to $15.6 million in 2010.<ref name=\"onehundredsixtyseven\"/><ref>{{cite news| last =Alspach| first =Kyle| title =HubSpot: We plan to be like HP, a huge company that lasts 100 years. But in Cambridge| newspaper =Boston Business Journal| date =December 15, 2011| url =http://www.bizjournals.com/boston/blog/startups/2011/12/hubspot-we-plan-to-be-like-hp-a-big.html| accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref>  Later that year HubSpot acquired Oneforty, the [[Twitter]] app store founded by [[Laura Fitton]].<ref name=\"onehundredseventytwo\">{{cite news| last =Rao| first =Leena| title =HubSpot Buys Social Media Management Platform And App Directory Oneforty| newspaper =TechCrunch| date =August 18, 2011| url =https://techcrunch.com/2011/08/18/hubspot-buys-social-media-management-platform-and-app-directory-oneforty/| accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"onehundredseventythree\">{{cite news| last =O\u2019Dell| first =Jolie| title =Twitter app store Oneforty acquired by HubSpot| newspaper =VentureBeat| date =August 18, 2011| url =https://venturebeat.com/2011/08/18/oneforty-acquisition/| accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref> The company also introduced new software for personalizing websites to each visitor.<ref>{{cite news| last =Alspach| first =Kyle| title =HubSpot: What we're working on now will change the Internet| newspaper =Boston Business Journal| date =December 14, 2011| url =http://www.bizjournals.com/boston/blog/startups/2011/12/hubspot-amazon-personalization-marketing.html| accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref> According to ''Forbes'', HubSpot started out targeting small companies but \"moved steadily upmarket to serve larger businesses of up to 1000 employees.\"<ref name=\"\u201ccrm\">{{cite news|first=Chuck|last=Schaeffer|url=http://www.crmsearch.com/hubspot-review.php|publisher=CRMSearch|title=HubSpot Marketing Software Review\u2014An Independent Marketing Software Analysis|accessdate=January 27, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite news|title=HubSpot Looks to Pounce as Traditional Marketing Gets \"Obliterated\"|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jjcolao/2012/03/15/hubspot-ready-to-pounce-as-traditional-marketing-gets-obliterated/|first=J.J.|last=Colao|date=March 15, 2012|accessdate=December 29, 2013|work=Forbes}}</ref> HubSpot filed for an initial public offering with the Securities and Exchange Commission on August 25, 2014, requesting they be listed on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] under the ticker symbol HUBS.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1404655/000119312514320044/d697256ds1.htm|title=S-1|publisher=}}</ref> In July 2017, HubSpot acquired Kemvi, which applies artificial intelligence and machine learning to help sales teams.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/07/25/hubspot-acquires-kemvi/|title=HubSpot acquires Kemvi to bring more AI into its sales and marketing platform|last=Ha|first=Anthony|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2017-11-02|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Software and services==\nHubSpot provides  tools for [[social media marketing]], [[content management]], [[web analytics]], [[landing pages]], [[customer support]], and [[search engine optimization]].<ref name=\"onehundredsixtyseven\"/><ref name=\"wsjj\">{{cite news|title=\nGoogle Ventures, Sequoia, Salesforce Give HubSpot $32M|date=March 8, 2011|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2011/03/08/google-ventures-sequoia-salesforce-give-hubspot-32m/|accessdate=December 27, 2013|first=Deborah|last=Gage}}</ref><ref name=\"harvard\"/><ref name=\"onehundredfiftythree\">{{cite news\n | last =McCarthy\n | first =Kevin\n | title =The Tech Behind HubSpot\n | newspaper =BostInno\n | date =May 26, 2011\n | url =http://bostinno.com/2011/05/26/the-tech-behind-hubspot/\n | accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2018/05/11/hubspot-service-hub/|title=HubSpot adds customer service tools to its marketing platform|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref>\nHubSpot has integration features for [[salesforce.com]], [[SugarCRM]], [[NetSuite]], [[Microsoft Dynamics CRM]] and others.<ref>{{cite news\n | last =Greenberg\n | first =Paul\n | title =CRM Watchlist 2012 Winners \u2013 The Marketing Mavens\n | newspaper =ZDNet\n | date =January 24, 2012\n | url =http://www.zdnet.com/blog/crm/crm-watchlist-2012-winners-the-marketing-mavens/4074\n | accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref>  There are also third-party services such as templates and extensions.<ref>{{citation|url=http://marketplace.hubspot.com/|title=Marketplace|publisher=HubSpot|accessdate=December 27, 2013}}</ref> Additionally, HubSpot offers consulting services and an online resource academy for learning inbound marketing tactics.<ref name=\"onehundredeighty\">{{cite news\n | last =Blackwell\n | first =Gerry\n | title =HubSpot: The Evolution of Marketing\n | publisher =Small Business Computing\n | date =January 16, 2008\n | url =http://www.smallbusinesscomputing.com/biztools/article.php/3722071/HubSpot-The-Evolution-of-Marketing.htm\n | accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"thirtysix\"/> It also hosts user group conferences and inbound marketing and certification programs.<ref name=\"thirtysix\">{{citation|url=http://academy.hubspot.com/|title=HubSpot Academy|accessdate=December 26, 2013|date=May 18, 2009}}</ref>  HubSpot promotes their [[inbound marketing]] concepts through their own marketing,<ref name=\"harvard\">{{citation|title=HubSpot: Inbound Marketing and Web 2.0|first1=Thomas|last1=Steenburgh|first2=Jilly |last2=Avery |first3= Naseem |last3= Dahod|date=January 24, 2011|url=http://hbr.org/product/hubspot-inbound-marketing-and-web-2-0/an/509049-PDF-ENG|accessdate=December 30, 2013}}</ref> and has been called \"a prolific creator of content\" such as blogs, social media, webinars and white papers.<ref name=\"\u201ccrm\"/>\n\nIn 2010, an article in the ''Harvard Business Review'' said that HubSpot's most effective inbound marketing feature was its free online tools.<ref name=\"afgty\">{{cite news|title=HubSpot\u2019s New Alerts Grader Cures Social Media Email Overload|url=http://bostinno.streetwise.co/2010/04/27/inundated-with-emails-try-hubspots-alert-grader/|publisher=BostInno|date=April 27, 2010|first=Kyle|last=Psaty|accessdate=December 28, 2013}}</ref> One such tool, the Marketing Grader, assessed and scored website performance.<ref name=\"onehundredeightytwo\">{{cite news| last =Ha| first =Anthony| title =Marketing software company HubSpot raises $12M| newspaper =VentureBeat| date =May 16, 2008| url =https://venturebeat.com/2008/05/16/marketing-software-company-hubspot-raises-12m/| accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"onehundredfive\">{{cite news\n | last =Gomer\n | first =Gregory\n | title =HubSpot Marketing Grader Launches: We Put 30 Boston Startups Head to Head #Deathmatch\n | newspaper =Bostinno\n | date =December 6, 2011\n | url =http://bostinno.com/2011/12/06/hubspot-marketing-grader-launches-we-put-30-boston-startups-head-to-head-deathmatch/\n | accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref> The company introduced a Twitter tracking feature in 2011.<ref name=\"onehundredsixtyeight\">{{cite news\n | last =Gomer\n | first =Gregory\n | title =HubSpot Powers Useful Tool to Track ReTweets, Suffers Unfortunate Name: WhoretweetedMe\n | publisher =BostonInno\n | date = August 10, 2011\n | url =http://bostinno.com/2011/08/10/hubspot-powers-useful-tool-to-track-retweets-suffers-unfortunate-name-whoretweetedme/\n | accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"onehundredseventyone\">{{cite news\n | last =Dugan\n | first =Lauren\n | title =Find Out Which Influencers Retweeted You\n | publisher =MediaBistro\n | date =August 16, 2011\n | url =http://www.mediabistro.com/alltwitter/find-out-which-influencers-retweeted-you_b12750\n | accessdate =February 27, 2012\n | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20120114134803/http://www.mediabistro.com/alltwitter/find-out-which-influencers-retweeted-you_b12750\n | archive-date =January 14, 2012\n | url-status =dead\n }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, HubSpot launched HubSpot Academy, an online training platform that provides various digital marketing training programs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hubspot.com/company-news/hubspot-academy-launches-new-content-marketing-certification-with-a-lesson-on-topic-clusters|title=HubSpot Academy Launches New Content Marketing Certification With a Lesson on Topic Clusters|last=Flanagan|first=Ellie|website=www.hubspot.com|access-date=2019-10-03}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Hubspot integrated [[Taboola]] on the dashboard, a global [[pay-per-click]] native ad network.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ppc.land/hubspot-is-now-connected-with-taboola/|title=HubSpot is now connected with Taboola|last=Rijo|first=Daniel|date=June 3, 2018|work=PPC Land|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Hubspot acquired PieSync, a customer data [[synchronization]] platform.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/hubspot-acquires-piesync-the-highest-reviewed-data-syncing-ipaas-to-enable-a-consistent-view-of-customers-across-hundreds-of-different-technologies-300950685.html | title=HubSpot Acquires PieSync | work=[[PR Newswire]] | date=November 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===HubSpot CRM Free===\nThe company launched '''HubSpot CRM Free''' in 2014.<ref name=\"Salager14\">{{cite news |title=The effect of HubSpot's CRM launch on Salesforce |last1=Salager |first1=Serge |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/12/10/is-hubspots-crm-launch-a-declaration-of-war-to-salesforce/ |newspaper=TechCrunch |date=10 December 2014 |accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> The CRM product tracks and manages interactions between a company and its customers and prospects. It enables companies to forecast revenue, measure sales team productivity, and report on revenue sources.<ref name=\"Brooks17\">{{cite web |url=https://www.businessnewsdaily.com/10071-best-crm-tools-startup.html |title=HubSpot review: Best CRM software for startups |author=Chad Brooks |date=12 July 2017 |publisher=Business News Daily |accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Maloney16\">{{cite news |title=14 free business tools to make your startup more successful in 2017 |last1=Maloney |first1=Kathleen |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/kathleen-maloney/14-free-business-tools-to_b_13718746.html |newspaper=[[HuffPost]] |date=19 December 2016 |accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"William17\">{{cite news |title=Best CRMs for SMBs in 2017 |last1=Williams |first1=Mike |url=http://www.techradar.com/news/software/business-software/10-crm-systems-small-businesses-should-know-1250344 |newspaper=[[TechRadar]] |date=13 July 2017 |accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> The [[software as a service]] product is free and integrates with [[Gmail]], [[G Suite]], [[Microsoft Office]] for [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], and other software.<ref name=\"Houpes15\">{{cite web |url=http://searchcrm.techtarget.com/feature/What-to-expect-from-the-HubSpot-CRM-platform |title=What to expect from the HubSpot CRM platform |author=T.J. Houpes |date=25 September 2015 |publisher=TechTarget |accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Tech industry reviews===\nHubSpot has been described as unique because it strives to provide its customers with an all-in-one approach.<ref name=\"onehundredfiftythree\"/><ref name=\"onehundredseventyeight\">{{cite news\n | last =Roush\n | first =Wade\n | title =Online Marketing for Dummies\u2014and for People with Better Things to Do\n | newspaper =Xconomy\n | date =August 24, 2007\n | url =http://www.xconomy.com/boston/2007/08/24/online-marketing-for-dummies-and-for-people-with-better-things-to-do/\n | accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref> A 2012 review in CRM Search said HubSpot was not the best business solution in each category but that taken as a whole it was the best \"marketing solution\" that combined many tools into one package.<ref name=\"\u201ccrm\"/> It identified HubSpot's \"strengths\" as the sophistication of its Call to Action (CTA) tool, its online ecosystem and its \"ease of use.\"  Its weakness was described as having \"more breadth than depth.\" The review said the lack of customization and design tools could be limiting and that it was missing advanced features such as [[Business Process Management]] (BPM) tools to manage workflow.<ref name=\"\u201ccrm\"/>\n\n===Conferences===\nHubSpot hosts an annual marketing conference for HubSpot users and partners called \"Inbound.\" The conference is typically located in Boston. In 2019, they had the largest of the conferences in the event history with a record of over 26,000 attendees.<ref name=\"onehundredeightyfive\">{{cite news\n | title =Takeaways from HubSpot INBOUND 2018\n | newspaper =CMS Newswire\n | date =February 7, 2019\n | url =https://www.cmswire.com/digital-marketing/takeaways-from-hubspot-inbound-2018/\n | accessdate =February 7, 2019 }}</ref><ref>https://gritdaily.com/recap-inbound-2019/</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn July 2015, Hubspot's CMO, Mike Volpe, was dismissed for violating HubSpot's code of business conduct after it was found that he tried to obtain a draft copy of the book ''[[Disrupted: My Misadventure in the Start Up Bubble]],'' written by his former employee [[Daniel Lyons]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.betaboston.com/news/2015/07/29/hubspot-fires-marketing-chief-sanctions-ceo-over-incident-involving-book-about-the-company/|title=HubSpot fires marketing chief, sanctions CEO over incident involving book about the company|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://fortune.com/disrupted-excerpt-hubspot-startup-dan-lyons/ My Year in Startup Hell], Dan Lyons in ''Fortune'', April 2016</ref> According to an article in the ''[[Boston Globe]]'', records obtained under the [[Freedom of Information Act]] indicated that HubSpot executives considered the book \"a financial threat to HubSpot\" and Volpe used \"tactics such as email hacking and extortion\" in the attempt to prevent the book from being published.<ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2016/03/23/documents-released-hubspot-probe-involving-author-dan-lyons/VZH4CN4kR5p7iyhsKEdwJI/story.html Extortion, hacking claims sparked HubSpot investigation, FBI records show], Boston Globe, 24 March 2016</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, after his book was published, Lyons wrote in the ''[[New York Times]]'' that HubSpot had a \"frat house\" atmosphere. He also called the company a \"digital sweatshop\" in which workers had little job security.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/10/opinion/sunday/congratulations-youve-been-fired.html|title=Congratulations! You\u2019ve Been Fired|first=Dan|last=Lyons|date=9 April 2016|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Later that month, HubSpot's founders gave an official response to the book, in which they addressed several, but not all, of Lyons' claims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2016/04/12/hubspot-finally-responds-to-dan-lyons-book/|title=HubSpot (Finally) Responds to Dan Lyons' Book|publisher=Fortune|date=12 April 2016|author=Primack, Dan}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe ''[[Boston Business Journal]]'' named HubSpot a \"Best Place to Work in 2012.\"<ref name=\"onehundredfiftysix\">{{cite news\n | last =Regan\n | first =Keith\n | title =Hubspot's West Coast attitude gets talent\n | newspaper =Boston Business Journal\n | date =June 10, 2011\n | url =http://www.bizjournals.com/boston/print-edition/2011/06/10/hubspots-west-coast-attitude-gets.html\n | accessdate =February 27, 2012 }}</ref> In 2015, the company was named the best large company to work for in Massachusetts by the ''Boston Globe''.<ref>Sarah Shemkus,[https://www.bostonglobe.com/magazine/2015/11/12/hubspot-tops-list-large-companies/sb6hujhzpWq7BFyYXbFvAP/story.html \"HubSpot Tops List of Large Companies,\"] Boston Globe, 12 November 2015 (page visited 16 June 2016)</ref><ref name=\"onehundredfiftytwo\">\n{{cite news\n | title =8 companies with the best vacation perks\n | newspaper =CNN Money\n | date =June 6, 2011\n | url =http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2011/pf/jobs/1105/gallery.best_vacation_policies.fortune/5.html\n | accessdate =February 27, 2012\n | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20120428064157/http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2011/pf/jobs/1105/gallery.best_vacation_policies.fortune/5.html\n | archive-date =April 28, 2012\n | url-status =dead\n | df =mdy-all\n }}\n</ref> In 2017, Hubspot was named 7th by CNBC as one of the best places to work in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/12/05/the-10-best-companies-to-work-for-in-2018.html|title=These are the best places to work in 2018|last=Dickler|first=Jessica|date=2017-12-06|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref> [[Glassdoor]] named Hubspot the best place to work in 2020.<ref>[https://www.glassdoor.com/Award/Best-Places-to-Work-LST_KQ0,19.htm Best Places to Work 2020] [[Glassdoor]]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book\n | last =Lyons\n | first =Daniel\n | title =Disrupted: My Misadventure in the Start Up Bubble\n | publisher =Hachette Books\n | year =2016\n | isbn =978-0316306089 }}\n* {{cite book\n | last =Halligan\n | first =Brian |author2=David Meerman Scott |author3=Dharmesh Shah\n | title =Inbound Marketing: Get Found Using Google, Social Media and Blogs\n | publisher =John Wiley & Sons, Inc.\n | year =2010\n | isbn =978-0-470-49931-3 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|HubSpot}}\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.hubspot.com}}\n*[https://blog.hubspot.com Hubspot Blog]\n*[https://academy.hubspot.com Hubspot Academy]\n\n{{Portal bar|Business|Companies|Economics|Internet|United States|Society}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hubspot}}\n[[Category:Technology companies based in the Boston area]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Cambridge, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Marketing companies established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Digital marketing companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Search engine optimization]]\n[[Category:Software companies based in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Web analytics]]\n[[Category:Marketing software]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:CRM software companies]]\n[[Category:Software companies of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Ammaiya services", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HubSpot"}
{"title_page": "Michael McKean", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Michael McKean\n| image = Michael_McKean_1999.jpg\n| caption = McKean in 1999\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1947|10|17}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| birth_name = Michael John McKean\n| occupation = Actor, comedian, writer, composer, musician\n| years_active = 1973\u2013present\n|education = [[Carnegie Mellon University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Fine Arts|BFA]])}}<br>[[New York University]] {{small|([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])}}\n| spouse = {{marriage|Susan Russell<br>|1970|1993|reason=divorced}}<br />{{marriage|[[Annette O'Toole]]<br>|1999}}\n| children = 2\n}}\n\n'''Michael John McKean''' (born October 17, 1947) is an American actor, comedian, and musician known for various roles in film and telelvision such as Lenny Kosnowski in ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'', [[David St. Hubbins]] in ''[[This is Spinal Tap]]'', and [[Chuck McGill]] on ''[[Better Call Saul]]''.\n\nMcKean's first breakout role was annoying neighbor Lenny Kosnowski on the sitcom ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]''. In the mid-1990s, McKean spent two seasons as a cast member on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''. He has played roles in several [[Christopher Guest]] ensemble films, particularly as [[David St. Hubbins]], lead vocalist and co-lead guitarist of the fictional rock band [[Spinal Tap (band)|Spinal Tap]] in ''[[This Is Spinal Tap]]''. He co-wrote the song \"A Mighty Wind\" (from [[A Mighty Wind|the film of the same name]]), which won a [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media|Grammy Award]], as well as \"A Kiss at the End of the Rainbow\" from the same film, which was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Song]].\n\nMcKean portrayed [[Chuck McGill]], brother of [[Saul Goodman]], on the AMC drama series ''[[Better Call Saul]]'', for which he has received a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Guest Actor in a Drama Series]] in 2019.\n\n==Early life==\nMcKean was born October 17, 1947, in [[New York City]], the son of Ruth, a librarian, and Gilbert McKean, one of the founders of [[Decca Records]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20070090,00.html|title=It's Lenny & Squiggy|work=people.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924140033/http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20070090,00.html|archivedate=2015-09-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/63/Michael-McKean.html| title=Michael McKean Biography (1947\u2013)| publisher=FilmReference.com| accessdate=May 1, 2014| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140801055736/http://www.filmreference.com/film/63/Michael-McKean.html| archivedate=August 1, 2014}}</ref> and was raised in [[Sea Cliff, New York]], on [[Long Island]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.broadway.com/buzz/138088/michael-mckean-savors-the-taste-of-superior-donuts/ | title = Michael McKean Savors the Taste of Superior Donuts | first = Kathy | last = Henderson | date = October 26, 2009 | publisher = Broadway.com | accessdate = May 1, 2014 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140502010132/http://www.broadway.com/buzz/138088/michael-mckean-savors-the-taste-of-superior-donuts/ | archivedate = May 2, 2014 }}</ref> McKean is of [[Irish people|Irish]], English, Scottish, and some German and Dutch descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Michael-McKean/6000000015656402032|title=Michael John McKean|website=geni_family_tree|accessdate=1 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170917075719/https://www.geni.com/people/Michael-McKean/6000000015656402032|archivedate=17 September 2017}}</ref> He graduated from high school in 1965. In early 1967, he was briefly a member of the New York City \"baroque pop\" band [[The Left Banke]] and played on the \"Ivy, Ivy\" single ([[A-side and B-side|B-side]]: \"And Suddenly\").<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.miaminewtimes.com/music/qanda-with-michael-mckean-of-spinal-tap-appearing-at-the-fillmore-miami-beach-on-may-5-6446620/ | title = Q&A With Michael McKean of Spinal Tap, Appearing at the Fillmore Miami Beach on May 5! | first = Arielle | last = Castillo | date = April 24, 2009 | newspaper = Miami New Times | accessdate = February 28, 2018 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170518170355/http://www.miaminewtimes.com/music/qanda-with-michael-mckean-of-spinal-tap-appearing-at-the-fillmore-miami-beach-on-may-5-6446620 | archivedate = May 18, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.noise11.com/news/r-i-p-michael-browne-of-the-left-banke-1949-2015-20150321/ | title = R.I.P. Michael Brown of The Left Banke 1949-2015 | first = Roger | last = Wink | date = March 21, 2015 | publisher = The Noise Network | accessdate = February 28, 2018 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180302103859/http://www.noise11.com/news/r-i-p-michael-browne-of-the-left-banke-1949-2015-20150321 | archivedate = March 2, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMcKean began his career (as well as the characters of Lenny and Squiggy) in [[Pittsburgh]] while a student at [[Carnegie Mellon]]; [[David Lander]] was a fellow student at CMU. Their partnership grew after graduation as part of the comedy group [[The Credibility Gap]] with [[Harry Shearer]] in Los Angeles, but McKean's breakthrough came in 1976 when he and Lander joined the cast of ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'' portraying Lenny and Squiggy. McKean directed one episode, and the characters became something of a phenomenon, even releasing an album as ''[[Lenny and the Squigtones]]'' in 1979, which featured a young [[Christopher Guest]] on guitar (credited as ''Nigel Tufnel''\u2014the name Guest would use a few years later as part of the spoof [[rock music|rock]] band, [[Spinal Tap (band)|Spinal Tap]]). \"Foreign Legion of Love\" was a big hit for the Squigtones, with frequent play on the ''[[Dr. Demento#The Dr. Demento radio show|Dr. Demento Show]]''. McKean also played his character in an episode of ''[[Happy Days]]''. After leaving ''Laverne & Shirley'' in 1982, McKean played [[David St. Hubbins]] in the comedy ''[[This is Spinal Tap]]'' with both Guest and Shearer, and appeared in the soap opera spoof ''[[Young Doctors in Love]]''.\n\nMcKean quickly became a recognizable name in film and television, with appearances in films such as ''[[Used Cars]]'' (1980), ''[[Clue (film)|Clue]]'' (1985), ''[[Planes, Trains and Automobiles]]'' (1987), ''[[Earth Girls Are Easy]]'' (1988), and taking a lead role in ''[[Short Circuit 2]]'' (1988).\n\n===1990s===\nIn 1990, McKean appeared opposite [[Kiefer Sutherland]] and [[Dennis Hopper]] in the American [[adventure comedy]] ''[[Flashback (1990 film)|Flashback]]''. That same year, McKean was part of an ensemble cast in the television series ''[[Grand (TV series)|Grand]]'' on [[NBC]], which, however, only aired for a short time. In 1991, McKean co-wrote (with [[Christopher Guest]]) the second episode and later directed the final episode of the mock documentary series ''[[Morton & Hayes]]'', created by [[Phil Mishkin]] and [[Rob Reiner]].\n\nHaving already appeared as a musical guest and then host of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', McKean joined the cast from 1994 to 1995. At the age of 46, he was the oldest person ever to join the ''SNL'' cast at the time (later surpassed by [[Leslie Jones (comedian)|Leslie Jones]], who joined in 2014 at age 47),<ref name=\"lj\">{{cite web|url=http://www.komenlacounty.org/get-involved/komen-activities/special-events/comedy-for-the-cure.html|title=Comedy for the Cure|work=[[Susan G. Komen for the Cure]]|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218103356/http://www.komenlacounty.org/get-involved/komen-activities/special-events/comedy-for-the-cure.html|archivedate=December 18, 2014}}</ref> one of a handful of ''SNL'' cast members who weren't already hired to work behind the scenes (like ''SNL'''s numerous writers-turned-cast members) to appear on the show before becoming a cast member ,and the only one to be a musical guest and a host before becoming a cast member.<ref name=\"splitsider\">{{cite web|url=http://splitsider.com/2013/07/saturday-nights-children-michael-mckean-1994-1995|title=Saturday Night&#039;s Children: Michael McKean (1994-1995) {{!}} Splitsider|work=[[The Awl|Splitsider]]|last=Wright|first=Megh|date=July 9, 2013|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218103656/http://splitsider.com/2013/07/saturday-nights-children-michael-mckean-1994-1995|archivedate=December 18, 2014}}</ref> During this time, he also released a video follow-up to ''Spinal Tap'', played the villainous Mr. Dittmeyer in ''[[The Brady Bunch Movie]]'', and played the boss Gibby in the [[HBO]] series ''[[Dream On (TV series)|Dream On]]''. After leaving ''Saturday Night Live'', McKean spent a lot of time doing children's fare, voicing various TV shows and movies.\n\nMcKean then appeared in a number of movie roles, including the film adaptation of ''[[Memoirs of an Invisible Man (film)|Memoirs of an Invisible Man]]'' (1992), ''[[Coneheads (movie)|Coneheads]]'' (1993), ''[[Airheads]]'' (1994), and ''[[Radioland Murders]]'' (1994). In 1997, he performed the lead voice role in the video game ''[[Zork Grand Inquisitor]]'' as Dalboz of Gurth and also appeared in the 1999 films ''[[Teaching Mrs. Tingle]]'' and ''[[Mystery, Alaska]]''.\n\nMcKean's television guest appearances include ''[[The Simpsons]]'', ''[[Star Trek: Voyager]]'', ''[[Boy Meets World]]'', ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]'', ''[[Murphy Brown]]'', ''[[Lois and Clark: The New Adventures of Superman]]'', ''[[Friends]]'', and ''[[Caroline in the City]]''. In 1998, he guest starred in a two-part episode of ''[[The X-Files]]'' called \"Dreamland,\" in which his character, Morris Fletcher, switched bodies with [[Fox Mulder]]. The character was a success, and reappeared in 1999's \"Three of a Kind,\" an episode which focused on the recurring characters of [[The Lone Gunmen]]. The character appeared on their short-lived spin-off series in 2001, and then returned to ''The X-Files'' in its final season for an episode called \"Jump the Shark.\"\n\n===2000s===\n[[File:MichaelMcKeanJaneLynch06TIFF.jpg|thumb|right|McKean and [[Jane Lynch]] at the [[2006 Toronto International Film Festival]].]]\nMcKean reunited with Christopher Guest in ''[[Best in Show (film)|Best in Show]]'' (2000) and also appeared in ''[[Little Nicky]]'' (2000), ''[[The Guru (2002 film)|The Guru]]'' (2002), ''[[And Starring Pancho Villa as Himself]]'' (2003), and ''[[A Mighty Wind]]'' (2003), in which [[The Folksmen]] are played by the actors who played as [[Spinal Tap (band)|Spinal Tap]]. McKean had a regular role as the brassy, heavily made-up bandleader Adrian Van Voorhees in [[Martin Short]]'s [[Comedy Central]] series ''[[Primetime Glick]]''. He also had guest roles on such shows as ''[[Law & Order]]'', ''[[Family Guy]]'', ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]'', and ''[[Harvey Birdman, Attorney at Law]]''. He did voiceover work as Henry's cousin, Louie, on ''Oswald'', which coincidentally featured the voice of David Lander as Henry. And he lent his voice to an episode of [[Kevin Smith]]'s ''[[Clerks (animated series)|Clerks: The Animated Series]]'' that was never aired on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] but was included on the VHS and DVD versions of the series.\n\nIn 2003, he guest starred on ''[[Smallville (TV series)|Smallville]]'', the [[Superman]] prequel in which his wife, [[Annette O'Toole]], starred as [[Martha Kent]]. McKean played [[Perry White]], who ultimately becomes Clark Kent's boss. He had previously associated with the [[Superman]] universe in 1994 on the ''[[Lois & Clark: The New Adventures of Superman]]'' first-season episode \"Vatman,\" in which he played Dr. Fabian Leek, a cloning expert who creates a Superman clone that belonged to corporate mogul [[Lex Luthor]] ([[John Shea]]). Also, during his short stint on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', McKean played [[Perry White]] in a Superman spoof.\n\nIn 2003, he appeared in the Christopher Guest comedy ''[[A Mighty Wind]]''. He co-wrote several songs for the film, including ''A Mighty Wind'' (with Guest and [[Eugene Levy]]), which won the [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] for \"Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media\" and ''A Kiss at the End of the Rainbow'', which was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Song]].\n\nMcKean performed in the Broadway production of ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'' in 2004, and is apparently writing his own [[Musical theater|musical]] with O'Toole. He co-starred as Hines in a revival of ''[[The Pajama Game]]'' with [[Harry Connick, Jr.]] at the [[American Airlines Theatre]] in the first half of 2006. Also in 2006, McKean reunited with most of the cast of ''A Mighty Wind'' to film the comedy ''[[For Your Consideration (film)|For Your Consideration]]'' and appeared in the play ''Love Song'' on the stage in London. His musical interests led him to a starring role in the 2008 comedy air-drumming film ''[[Adventures of Power]]'', in which he was reunited with his co-star from ''For Your Consideration'', [[Jane Lynch]], in a story intended to honor the leaders and fighters of the 99% movement.<ref>{{YouTube|ObOKVM6U-7s|'IN THE AIR TONIGHT' from \"Adventures of Power\"}}. Retrieved May 11, 2012.</ref>\n\nMcKean was cast in the pilot episode of a remake of the British series ''[[The Thick of It (U.S. Series)|The Thick of It]]'' as the chief of staff. The pilot was directed by Guest. McKean starred in the fortieth anniversary [[Broadway theater|Broadway]] revival of [[Harold Pinter]]'s ''[[The Homecoming]]'', co-starring [[Ian McShane]], [[Raul Esparza]], [[Eve Best]], and [[James Frain]]. The show opened on December 9, 2007. In 2009, he starred in the Chicago-based [[Steppenwolf Theatre Company]]'s production of ''[[Superior Donuts]]'', by playwright [[Tracy Letts]].\n\n===2010s===\n[[File:Annette O'Toole and Michael McKean sing on Employee of the Month.jpg|thumb|Singer-songwriter spouses Annette O'Toole and Michael McKean perform their song \"Kiss at the End of the Rainbow\" on ''[[Employee of the Month (podcast)|Employee of the Month]]'' in 2016]]\nOn January 20, 2010, it was announced that Michael McKean would return to an episode of ''Smallville'' alongside his spouse, [[Annette O'Toole]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.tvguide.com/News/Michael-McKean-Returns-1014010.aspx|title= Michael McKean Returns to ''Smallville''|publisher= TVGuide.com|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100123031549/http://www.tvguide.com/News/Michael-McKean-Returns-1014010.aspx|archivedate= 2010-01-23}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2010, McKean won the ''Celebrity [[Jeopardy!]]'' tournament by defeating [[Jane Curtin]] and [[Cheech Marin]]. The earnings were donated to the International Myeloma Foundation in honor of McKean's friend Lee Grayson, who died of myeloma in 2004. In the summer of 2010, McKean took over the role of the Stage Manager in [[Thornton Wilder]]'s ''[[Our Town]]'' at the Barrow Street Playhouse in New York's Greenwich Village. His run ended on August 24, 2010. In 2011, McKean appeared on an episode of ''[[Sesame Street]]'' as a rock star looking for \"rocks\" to be in an all ROCK-band.\n\nIn April 2012, McKean began performing on Broadway in Gore Vidal's ''The Best Man''. On May 22, 2012, McKean was hit by a car in New York City, suffering a broken leg. His part was filled by James Lecesne. On June 1, 2012, McKean was released from the hospital to begin physical rehabilitation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/michael-mckean-car-accident-331761|title=Michael McKean released from hospital to begin physical rehab|work=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Erin|last=Carlson|date=May 31, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531191723/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/michael-mckean-car-accident-331761|archivedate=May 31, 2012}}</ref> He also appeared in the HBO comedy series ''[[Family Tree (TV series)|Family Tree]]'' in early 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5j-m-OXufny02gqXNToHb8-Peus2Q?docId=1c18efba31a143acb2d7525bc94a03cc|title = Injury forces Michael McKean out of Broadway show |publisher=ap.org|accessdate=May 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2014, McKean played [[J. Edgar Hoover]] in Broadway previews of Robert Schenkkan's Lyndon B. Johnson bio-play, ''[[All the Way (play)|All the Way]]'', starring Emmy winner [[Bryan Cranston]] as [[Lyndon B. Johnson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadway.com/buzz/174448/lyndon-b-johnson-bio-play-all-the-way-starring-bryan-cranston-begins-performances-on-broadway|title=Lyndon B. Johnson Bio-Play All the Way, Starring Bryan Cranston, Begins Performances on Broadway|work=Broadway.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305025303/http://www.broadway.com/buzz/174448/lyndon-b-johnson-bio-play-all-the-way-starring-bryan-cranston-begins-performances-on-broadway/|archivedate=2014-03-05}}</ref> In 2015 through 2017, he appeared as a regular cast member in the first three seasons of ''[[Breaking Bad]]'' [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]] ''[[Better Call Saul]]'', in the role of the central character's older brother Chuck McGill \u2013 a new character created for the series<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/537429/michael-mckean-cast-in-the-breaking-bad-prequel-better-call-saul-find-out-who-he-s-playing|title=Michael McKean Cast in the Breaking Bad Prequel Better Call Saul: Find Out Who He's Playing|work=E! Online|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502033315/http://www.eonline.com/news/537429/michael-mckean-cast-in-the-breaking-bad-prequel-better-call-saul-find-out-who-he-s-playing|archivedate=2014-05-02}}</ref> \u2013 and occasionally in the [[Better Call Saul (season 4)|fourth season]]. \n\nIn 2015, McKean also began hosting the [[Cooking Channel]] television series ''[[Food: Fact or Fiction?]]'' This lighthearted show takes a look at food urban legends and features him both as host and narrator to some segments within each episode.\n\nHe played Sgt. Shadwell in the 2019 [[Good Omens (TV series)|television mini-series adaptation]] of the novel ''[[Good Omens]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/09/good-omens-jack-whitehall-michael-mckean-miranda-richardson-join-cast-amazon-prime-bbc-two-1202170543/|title=\u2018Good Omens\u2019: Jack Whitehall, Michael McKean, Miranda Richardson & Adria Arjona Join Amazon Series|first1=Erik|last1=Pedersen|website=Deadline.com|date=September 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Characters on ''SNL'' ==\n===Recurring characters on ''SNL''===\n*Anthony, the weatherman from \"Good Morning, Brooklyn\"\n\n===Celebrity impersonations on ''SNL''===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n*[[Bill Clinton]] (after [[Phil Hartman]] left at the end of season 19)\n*[[Jimmy Carter]]\n*[[Robert Evans (producer)|Robert Evans]]\n*[[John Tesh]]\n*[[Robert Shapiro (lawyer)|Robert Shapiro]]\n*[[Spalding Gray]]\n*[[Tom Skerritt]]\n*[[Vincent Price]]\n*[[Richard Gephardt]]\n*[[Jeffrey Dahmer]]\n*[[Howard Stern]]\n*[[Donald E. Belfi]]\n*[[Adam West]]\n*[[Elvis Costello]]\n*[[George F. Will]]\n*[[Gary Busey]]\n*[[Patrick Stewart]]\n}}\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class = \"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class = \"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''Cracking Up''\n| Various characters\n|\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[1941 (film)|1941]]''\n| Willy\n|\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Used Cars]]''\n| Eddie Winslow\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Young Doctors in Love]]''\n| Dr. Simon August\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[This Is Spinal Tap]]''\n| [